Salvador Dali's "marsupial centauresses", possessing a kangaroo pouch, which Dali saw as a potential useful adaptation to attenuate the psychological "trauma of birth", similar to a parachute. The child is able to return to the womb and slowly habituate itself to harsher reality.

Salvador Dali is very interesting to me, because he's the type of artist where someone asks him "oh why does the hippo in your painting have an umbrella?" and he responds "so the city guard doesn't shoot it with a cannon" and everyone laughs "oh he is so eccentric and surreal"...

... but if you actually read his writings, he's just using these images as idiosyncratic symbols in a very sensible way that is easy to understand once you know their meaning and nothing is really "random" at all. He does lean into it ofc., but it's not just empty mystifications.

He even suggests that the Chilean army learn Indian tactics like sending smoke signals as comms instead of using radio etc. He also uses the Alex Jones-ian term "INFOWAR". Funnily enough Michael Aquino who is on the other side of this also was obsessed with Indian tribal warfare.

Contrary Pancake had a post about how Jones took the term "infowar" from Thomas Moorer who was a joint chiefs of staff chairman and spied on Nixon. I guess it gets very 5D chessy. But basically very low tech beats very high tech and to counter "MindWar" you need sticks and stones
